**Answer**

The “extra” 1 % that you see in the example is not a separate tax.  
It is the **tax‑on‑tax** that arises because the VAT is calculated on the
price that already contains the previous VAT.  
When the price is increased by 1 % the VAT amount itself increases, so the
total tax rises by more than 1 %.  
In the example the 1 % increase in the price leads to a 1.02 % increase in
the VAT, which is why the total tax goes from 10 % to 11.02 % (10 % + 1.02 %).
This is a normal effect of the way VAT is applied, not a special
additional tax.